\newcommand{\msbar}{\overline{\text{MS}}}

\newtheorem{proposition}{Proposition}

\title{Soddy curvature of the Koide lepton triple and the strange-quark mass}

\date{April 2026}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
\noindent
The Koide relation $Q = (\sum m_\ell)/(\sum \sqrt{m_\ell})^2 = 2/3$ for the charged leptons has held to one part in $10^5$ for over forty years without an accepted derivation. Kocik~\cite{Kocik2012} observed that this relation has a Descartes-circle interpretation: identifying lepton mass square roots with circle curvatures, the Koide relation is the precise condition under which the algebraically natural combination $\mathcal{F} \equiv (\sum \sqrt{m_\ell}) - \sqrt{\sum m_\ell}$ coincides with the outer Soddy curvature $e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$. We compute this curvature for the observed lepton triple and report a numerical observation: $\mathcal{F}^2 = 95.113$~MeV reproduces the strange-quark $\msbar$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau$ within current lattice precision (residual $-0.019$~MeV against a total uncertainty of $\pm 0.814$~MeV). Under a Koide-conditioned null model with a log-uniform prior on triples, the observed match arises in $0.58\%$ of valid samples (95\% CI $[0.49\%,\,0.68\%]$). The hit fraction is robust to four alternative prior choices (range $0.26\%$--$0.58\%$, fold variation $2.2$). Of eight lepton-derived scale prescriptions tested, only $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ produces a hit; the next-best alternatives miss by $\pm 2\sigma$. We present this as a structural observation, not a derivation or a prediction. We make no claim about an underlying mechanism. We disclose the order of operations leading to the observation and report scale, input, prior, and filter sensitivities along with the error budget decomposition.
\end{abstract}

%======================================================================
\section{Introduction}
%======================================================================

The Koide relation~\cite{Koide1982,Koide1983}
\begin{equation}
Q \;\equiv\; \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{\big(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\big)^2} \;=\; \frac{2}{3}
\label{eq:koide}
\end{equation}
holds for the observed charged lepton pole masses to one part in $10^5$. Using the PDG~2024 values~\cite{PDG2024} ($m_e = 0.5109989$~MeV, $m_\mu = 105.6584$~MeV, $m_\tau = 1776.93 \pm 0.09$~MeV), one computes $Q = 0.666661$. Although the relation is not part of the standard Standard-Model curriculum, it has been the subject of continuous theoretical investigation since 1981, with derivation attempts, extensions to the neutrino and quark sectors, and geometric reinterpretations appearing across the intervening four decades; we cite the Rivero--Gsponer review~\cite{RiveroGsponer2005} as an entry point and~\cite{Foot1994,Sumino2009,RodejohannZhang2011,Rivero2011,Krolikowski2014} as representative further reading. We treat~(\ref{eq:koide}) as an empirical input.

In 2012, Kocik~\cite{Kocik2012} observed that the Koide relation has a Descartes-circle interpretation: identifying $k_i \equiv \sqrt{m_i}$ for $i \in \{e, \mu, \tau\}$, the lepton mass square roots are realizable as three of four curvatures of a mutually tangent Soddy circle configuration governed by the Descartes circle theorem. The Koide value $Q = 2/3$ is precisely the condition under which the algebraically natural combination $e_1 - \sqrt{p_2}$ formed from the leptons coincides with the geometrically determined outer Soddy curvature $e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$ of the configuration. We make this statement precise as Proposition~\ref{prop:koide_descartes} below. Kocik's own treatment uses a generalized intersecting-circle Descartes formula and explicitly sets the fourth curvature to zero (a degenerate ``line'' circle); he does not compute the non-trivial fourth curvature, and he does not connect any geometric quantity to a quark mass. Our contribution is precisely that step.

We extend Kocik's construction by computing the outer Soddy curvature for the observed lepton triple, denoting it $\mathcal{F}$, and reporting a numerical observation: $\mathcal{F}^2$ equals the strange-quark $\msbar$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale $\mu = \sum m_\ell$ within current lattice precision. We make no theoretical claim. The contribution of this paper is the computation of $\mathcal{F}$ within Kocik's framework and the disclosure of the resulting numerical match, together with a quantification of how unlikely such a match is under a Koide-conditioned null and how stable that quantification is under alternative priors, scale prescriptions, and filter cutoffs.

%======================================================================
\section{The Koide relation as a Descartes condition}
%======================================================================

We summarize the Kocik construction~\cite{Kocik2012} for completeness and to fix notation.

The Descartes circle theorem~\cite{Coxeter1968} states that four mutually tangent circles in the plane, with curvatures $k_1, k_2, k_3, k_4$, satisfy
\begin{equation}
(k_1 + k_2 + k_3 + k_4)^2 \;=\; 2\,(k_1^2 + k_2^2 + k_3^2 + k_4^2).
\label{eq:descartes}
\end{equation}
Given three curvatures $k_1, k_2, k_3$, equation~(\ref{eq:descartes}) is a quadratic in $k_4$ with two real solutions
\begin{equation}
k_4^{\,\pm} \;=\; (k_1 + k_2 + k_3) \;\pm\; 2\sqrt{k_1 k_2 + k_2 k_3 + k_1 k_3},
\label{eq:soddy}
\end{equation}
corresponding respectively to the inner and outer Soddy circles tangent to the original three. By convention, the larger-curvature solution $k_4^{\,+}$ corresponds to the smaller circle (the inner Soddy circle, nestled in the gap between the original three), and the smaller-curvature solution $k_4^{\,-}$ corresponds to the larger circle (the outer Soddy circle, conventionally drawn enclosing the original three). The relevant quantity for our purposes is the outer curvature $k_4^{\,-} = e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$.

\begin{proposition}[Koide and the outer Soddy curvature, after Kocik~\cite{Kocik2012}]
\label{prop:koide_descartes}
Identify $k_i \equiv \sqrt{m_i}$ for $i \in \{e, \mu, \tau\}$. Let $e_1 = \sum_i \sqrt{m_i}$, $e_2 = \sum_{i<j} \sqrt{m_i m_j}$, and $p_2 = \sum_i m_i$. The outer Soddy curvature of the Descartes configuration $(k_e, k_\mu, k_\tau)$ is
\begin{equation}
k_4^{\,-} \;=\; e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}.
\label{eq:k4_geometric}
\end{equation}
The algebraically simpler expression
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F} \;\equiv\; e_1 - \sqrt{p_2} \;=\; \big(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\big) - \sqrt{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}
\label{eq:F_alg}
\end{equation}
coincides with $k_4^{\,-}$ if and only if the Koide relation $Q \equiv p_2/e_1^2 = 2/3$ holds exactly.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
The Soddy form follows from solving the quadratic~(\ref{eq:descartes}) for $k_4$ given $k_1, k_2, k_3$, using the identity $e_1^2 = p_2 + 2 e_2$ to simplify the discriminant; the smaller-curvature root is $k_4^{\,-} = e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$. Setting $e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2} = e_1 - \sqrt{p_2}$ yields $4 e_2 = p_2$. Combined with $e_1^2 = p_2 + 2 e_2$, this gives $e_1^2 = p_2 + p_2/2 = (3/2) p_2$, equivalently $p_2/e_1^2 = 2/3$, which is the Koide condition. Conversely, if $Q = 2/3$ then $e_2 = e_1^2/6 = p_2/4$, so $2\sqrt{e_2} = \sqrt{p_2}$ and the two expressions agree. \qed
\end{proof}

Proposition~\ref{prop:koide_descartes} gives the precise content of Kocik's geometric reading of Koide. The Koide relation is the statement that the dimensionally natural combination $e_1 - \sqrt{p_2}$, formed without reference to circles, is in fact the outer Soddy curvature of the Descartes configuration whose three input curvatures are the lepton mass square roots. The observed leptons satisfy $Q = 0.666661$, so the equality of~(\ref{eq:k4_geometric}) and~(\ref{eq:F_alg}) holds to one part in $10^5$. In what follows we use the form~(\ref{eq:F_alg}) for numerical convenience and treat $\mathcal{F}$ as the (Koide-approximate) outer Soddy curvature; we quantify the residual difference numerically in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}.

Although Kocik~\cite{Kocik2012} gives the geometric identification of Koide as a Descartes condition, to our knowledge the outer Soddy curvature $\mathcal{F}$ has not previously been computed and compared with hadronic observables. We discuss the relation of the present work to existing Koide-quark literature, in particular Rivero's algebraic ``waterfall''~\cite{Rivero2011} and the Rodejohann--Zhang quark Koide tuples~\cite{RodejohannZhang2011}, in Section~\ref{sec:notclaims}.

%======================================================================
\section{The outer Soddy curvature of the lepton triple}
%======================================================================

We have defined $\mathcal{F}$ in equation~(\ref{eq:F_alg}). Two further remarks before computing it.

\paragraph{The function $\mathcal{F}$ in Kocik's framework.}
$\mathcal{F}$ is not chosen from a catalog of symmetric polynomials. Once the Koide relation is read as a Descartes condition (Proposition~\ref{prop:koide_descartes}), the natural Descartes-determined quantities of dimension $[\text{mass}]^{1/2}$ are the two Soddy curvatures $k_4^{\pm} = e_1 \pm 2\sqrt{e_2}$. The choice between them is binary (inner versus outer), not a continuous selection. We adopt the outer curvature, the smaller of the two and the one corresponding to the larger circle in the Descartes configuration. This binary choice, along with the choice of integer power $n$ when comparing $\mathcal{F}^n$ to a quark mass and the choice of comparison quark, contributes to the look-elsewhere effect that we quantify explicitly in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}; the structural narrowing provided by Kocik's framework is real but partial, and we do not claim that $\mathcal{F}$ is the unique observable one could extract from the construction.

\paragraph{Numerical value.}
At the PDG~2024 central charged-lepton pole masses,
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F} \;=\; 9.7528\;\text{MeV}^{1/2}, \qquad \mathcal{F}^2 \;=\; 95.1134\;\text{MeV}.
\label{eq:F_value}
\end{equation}
The propagated uncertainty from PDG lepton inputs is $\sigma_{\mathcal{F}^2} = 0.010$~MeV (Section~\ref{sec:robustness}), dominated by the tau mass uncertainty. The corresponding geometric quantity $k_4^{\,-} = e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2} = 9.752607~\text{MeV}^{1/2}$ agrees with the algebraic $\mathcal{F} = 9.752823~\text{MeV}^{1/2}$ to one part in $10^5$, the precision at which Koide holds; the corresponding difference in $\mathcal{F}^2$ is $0.004$~MeV, well below the lepton-side error budget of $0.010$~MeV. In what follows we use $\mathcal{F}$ throughout and report the comparison with $k_4^{\,-}$ once, here.

%======================================================================
\section{The observation}
%======================================================================

Evaluate the strange-quark $\msbar$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale,
\begin{equation}
\mu_\star \;\equiv\; m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau \;=\; 1883.1\;\text{MeV},
\end{equation}
by running the FLAG~2024 lattice average~\cite{FLAG2024} $m_s^{\msbar}(2~\text{GeV}) = 93.5 \pm 0.8$~MeV (for $N_f = 2{+}1{+}1$) via four-loop QCD~\cite{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$. This gives
\begin{equation}
m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star) \;=\; 95.132 \pm 0.814\;\text{MeV},
\end{equation}
where the uncertainty includes lattice input, the running of $\alpha_s$, charm-threshold matching, and four-loop truncation, with the lattice contribution dominating; we decompose this in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}. Both inputs are in the $\msbar$ scheme; the lattice average is the standard FLAG $\msbar$ result and we run it in $\msbar$. Comparing,
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}^2 - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star) \;=\; -0.019\;\text{MeV},
\label{eq:residual}
\end{equation}
or about $-0.023$ standard deviations of the lattice uncertainty. The PDG~2024 value $m_s^{\msbar}(2~\text{GeV}) = 93.5 \pm 0.8$~MeV gives a numerically identical result; the agreement does not depend on the choice between FLAG and PDG averaging.

We deliberately avoid framing~(\ref{eq:residual}) as a precision-significance claim. The residual is small in units of the lattice uncertainty, but the meaningful question is not how many standard deviations separate $\mathcal{F}^2$ from $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$; it is whether the structural setup that produced $\mathcal{F}$ would, under a reasonable null, generically produce numbers near $m_s$ at the natural scale. We address that question in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}.

\paragraph{Methodological note on order of operations.}
We disclose the order of operations leading to this observation, because it bears on the look-elsewhere assessment in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}. The author was investigating Kocik's geometric reading~\cite{Kocik2012} of the Koide relation and computed the fourth (outer Soddy) curvature of the Koide-saturating lepton triple as a geometric question, with the original motivation being whether the missing fourth curvature might admit a particle interpretation. The numerical agreement $\mathcal{F}^2 \approx m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$ was noticed only after the geometric computation was complete, on comparison with a previously consulted reference value for the strange-quark mass. The function $\mathcal{F}$ was therefore not selected from a class of candidate symmetric polynomials of lepton masses; it was determined by Kocik's framework. The choice of evaluation scale, however, deserves separate scrutiny: $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ is the natural mass scale of the lepton triple in the same dimensional sense that $\mathcal{F}$ is the natural curvature, but it is not the only candidate. We address that selection freedom empirically in Section~\ref{sec:scale_alternatives}.

%======================================================================
\section{Robustness}
\label{sec:robustness}
%======================================================================

We report robustness checks across six axes: (i) propagation of input uncertainties and decomposition of the error budget, (ii) continuous scale sensitivity around $\mu_\star$, (iii) discrete alternative scale prescriptions, (iv) a tight null-model test conditioned on the specific structural claim, (v) sensitivity of the null result to the prior, (vi) a loose null-model test admitting expanded look-elsewhere, together with the sensitivity of both nulls to the lower-cutoff filter on $\mu_\star$. All computations are reproducible from the open-source code accompanying this paper~\cite{KoideSoddyCode}.

\subsection{Input sensitivity and error budget}

Propagating PDG~2024 lepton uncertainties through~(\ref{eq:F_alg}) yields $\sigma_{\mathcal{F}^2}^{\text{lepton}} = 0.010$~MeV, dominated by $\sigma_{m_\tau} = 0.09$~MeV. This is to be combined with the running uncertainty on $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$. We decompose the latter by varying each input independently and re-running:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lc}
\toprule
Source & $\sigma$ contribution (MeV) \\
\midrule
FLAG lattice $m_s(2~\text{GeV}) = 93.5 \pm 0.8$ & $0.814$ \\
$\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$ & $0.051$ \\
Charm threshold $m_c(m_c) = 1.273 \pm 0.005$~GeV & $0.000$ \\
Four-loop truncation (4L vs 3L) & $0.039$ \\
\midrule
Quadrature sum & $0.817$ \\
Reported total at $\mu_\star$ & $0.814$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
The quadrature sum agrees with the directly reported total to $0.003$~MeV, confirming that the uncertainty propagation is internally consistent and that the lattice input dominates by an order of magnitude over all other sources. Combined with the lepton-side budget, lepton inputs contribute approximately $0.02\%$ of the total error budget; the remaining $99.98\%$ comes from the lattice strange-quark mass. The lepton side of~(\ref{eq:residual}) is essentially exact at present precision.

\subsection{Continuous scale sensitivity}

We compute $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu)$ for $\mu/\mu_\star \in [0.5, 4.0]$ and compare against the constant $\mathcal{F}^2$. The agreement degrades monotonically away from $\mu_\star$, with residual reaching $-30\sigma$ at $\mu = 0.5\,\mu_\star$. The intervals over which $|\mathcal{F}^2 - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu)|$ remains within one and two standard deviations of $\sigma_{m_s}(\mu)$ are
\begin{align}
\text{1$\sigma$ window:} \quad &\mu \in [1845,\,1940]\;\text{MeV} \;\;\approx\;\mu_\star (1 \pm 2.5\%),\\
\text{2$\sigma$ window:} \quad &\mu \in [1789,\,1996]\;\text{MeV} \;\;\approx\;\mu_\star (1 \pm 5.5\%).
\end{align}
The 1$\sigma$ window is narrow (about $\pm 2.5\%$), confirming that the relation is picking out a specific scale rather than holding broadly across hadronic energies. Crucially, $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ is exactly fixed by the lepton inputs, with no continuous adjustability: the agreement at $\mu_\star$ is not the result of choosing $\mu$ to optimize a fit, because $\mu_\star$ is determined by the same data ($m_e, m_\mu, m_\tau$) that determines $\mathcal{F}$.

\subsection{Alternative scale prescriptions}
\label{sec:scale_alternatives}

The continuous scan above shows that the relation is sharp at $\mu_\star$, but does not address whether $\mu_\star$ is the unique \emph{natural} scale among candidates derivable from lepton masses alone. We test eight alternative lepton-derived prescriptions, computing $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu)$ at each and comparing against the constant $\mathcal{F}^2 = 95.1134$~MeV:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Prescription & $\mu$ (MeV) & Hit (within $1\sigma$)? \\
\midrule
$\mu_\star = m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau$ (baseline) & $1883.10$ & yes ($-0.02\sigma$) \\
$m_\mu + m_\tau$ & $1882.59$ & yes (trivially equivalent) \\
$m_\tau$ & $1776.93$ & no ($-2.0\sigma$) \\
$2~\text{GeV}$ (conventional reference, not lepton-derived) & $2000.00$ & no ($+2.0\sigma$) \\
$(m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau)/3$ & $\phantom{0}627.70$ & non-perturbative \\
$\sqrt{m_\mu m_\tau}$ & $\phantom{0}432.92$ & non-perturbative \\
$(m_e m_\mu m_\tau)^{1/3}$ & $\phantom{000}47.43$ & non-perturbative \\
$3/(1/m_e + 1/m_\mu + 1/m_\tau)$ (harmonic) & $\phantom{0000}1.53$ & non-perturbative \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
Of the four prescriptions in the perturbative regime ($\mu \gtrsim 1$~GeV), only $\sum m_\ell$ and the trivially equivalent $m_\mu + m_\tau$ produce hits. The next-best lepton-derived alternative ($m_\tau$ alone) misses by $-2.0\sigma$, and the conventional non-lepton reference scale of $2$~GeV misses by $+2.0\sigma$. Four further candidates fall below the perturbative regime and we report them as non-perturbative rather than excluding them. Within the perturbative regime, the match is specific to $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$; it is not generic across reasonable lepton-derived prescriptions.

\subsection{Tight null-model test}
\label{sec:null_tight}

The relevant question is: under a Koide-conditioned prior on lepton triples, how often does $\mathcal{F}^2$ land within current lattice precision of $m_s^{\msbar}$ at the natural scale of that triple? We construct the null as follows.

Sample candidate triples $(m_1, m_2, m_3)$ with $m_3$ drawn log-uniformly from $[10^0, 10^4]$~MeV, $m_1$ drawn log-uniformly from $[10^{-3}, 10^{-1}]\cdot m_3$, and $m_2$ solved analytically from the Koide condition $Q(m_1, m_2, m_3) = 2/3$ in the physical range $m_1 < m_2 < m_3$. Discard triples for which no real $m_2$ exists in this range. Verify $|Q - 2/3| < 10^{-5}$ for each retained triple. The sampling yields $25{,}485$ valid triples out of $10^5$ samples; the remaining samples were excluded because the natural scale $\mu_\star^{(i)} \equiv m_1 + m_2 + m_3$ fell below $1$~GeV, where four-loop QCD running is not reliable, so the test is undefined for those triples on methodological grounds rather than excluded post hoc. We verify in Section~\ref{sec:filter} that the result is stable when this cutoff is varied.

For each valid triple, compute $\mathcal{F}^{(i)}$ and $\mu_\star^{(i)}$, run $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star^{(i)})$ from the FLAG 2~GeV input, and record a hit if $|\mathcal{F}^{(i)\,2} - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star^{(i)})| < \sigma_{m_s}(\mu_\star^{(i)})$. Of $25{,}485$ valid triples, $147$ produced hits. The hit fraction is
\begin{equation}
p_{\text{tight}} \;=\; 0.5768\%, \qquad
95\%\text{ Clopper--Pearson CI:}\;[0.49\%,\,0.68\%].
\label{eq:tight_null}
\end{equation}
The distribution of $(\mathcal{F}^{(i)\,2} - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star^{(i)}))/\sigma_{m_s}$ across the $25{,}485$ valid samples spans roughly $\pm 50$ standard deviations; the observed lepton triple sits within the central $\pm 1\sigma$ window, which is the rare outcome quantified by~(\ref{eq:tight_null}).

\subsection{Prior sensitivity}
\label{sec:prior_sensitivity}

The hit fraction~(\ref{eq:tight_null}) depends on the choice of prior over Koide-saturating triples. The log-uniform prior used above is one reasonable choice but not the only one. We re-run the tight null under three additional priors selected to span the space of reasonable alternatives:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Prior & Hit fraction & 95\% CI \\
\midrule
A: log-uniform $m_3 \in [10^0, 10^4]$~MeV (baseline) & $0.58\%$ & $[0.49,\,0.68]$ \\
B: log-uniform $m_3 \in [10^{-1}, 10^5]$~MeV (wider range) & $0.37\%$ & $[0.31,\,0.45]$ \\
C: log-uniform $m_1/m_3 \in [10^{-4}, 10^{-2}]$ (smaller ratio) & $0.56\%$ & $[0.47,\,0.66]$ \\
D: linear-uniform on $m_3$ and $m_1/m_3$ (stress test) & $0.26\%$ & $[0.23,\,0.30]$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
All four priors give hit fractions in the range $0.26\%$--$0.58\%$, with maximum-to-minimum fold variation of $2.2$. The deliberately adversarial linear prior (D), which heavily weights heavy triples and is not natural for mass-hierarchy problems, lowers the hit fraction rather than raising it. No reasonable prior we tested raises the hit fraction above $1\%$. We conclude that the qualitative rarity of the observation is robust to the choice of prior within the class we have tested, although the specific hit fraction is prior-dependent at the factor-of-two level.

\subsection{Loose null-model test and filter sensitivity}
\label{sec:filter}

To bound the residual look-elsewhere effect across a broader claim, we test $\mathcal{F}^n$ for $n \in \{1, 2, 3\}$ against each of $\{m_u, m_d, m_s, m_c, m_b\}$ at the natural scale $\mu_\star^{(i)}$ of each triple, counting a triple as a hit if any of the $15$ comparisons agrees within current lattice $1\sigma$. Across the same $25{,}485$ valid triples, the overall hit fraction is
\begin{equation}
p_{\text{loose}} \;=\; 0.812\%, \qquad
95\%\text{ Clopper--Pearson CI:}\;[0.71\%,\,0.93\%],
\label{eq:loose_null}
\end{equation}
only marginally larger than $p_{\text{tight}}$. The breakdown by quark and integer power is shown in Table~\ref{tab:loose}. Up- and down-quark hits at $n = 1$ are physically excluded by mass dimension ($\mathcal{F}^1 \sim 10$~MeV is too large for $m_u, m_d$). Strange hits at $n = 2$ dominate, accounting for $147/207 \approx 71\%$ of all hits in the loose null. Charm hits at $n = 3$ and bottom hits at $n = 3$ exist for some triples in the prior, but the observed lepton triple is not among them.

